description:
How to Avoid Bringing
Coronavirus Home: A Checklist
This checklist is by Dr Bill Griggs, former trauma services director in Australia's Royal Adelaide Hospital.
According to Dr. Griggs, he devised the list in response to requests from “non-medical" friends.
Print this infographic and use it as a reminder to help avoid bringing covid-19 at home.
Leaving home
The principle here is to prepare so that you can safely and
easily decontaminate when you return home.
Remove all below-elbow hand and arm wear, watches,
jewellery etc. They all stay home. You want to be able
to wash thoroughly when you get home and you don't
want to deal with crevices in these items. Wear short
sleeves so you can easily wash your hands and
forearms when you get home.
Leave your wallet/handbag home.
Rationalise your keys. Just the ones
you need this time. If you need to
take things such as personal hygiene
items, medicine etc, put these in a
disposable brown paper bag.
Your phone goes into a ziploc
bag. Avoid using your phone
as much as possible while out.
V O manage without it for a while.
No social media. You can
Credit card and photo ID
go into ziplock bags too.
Wear shoes that live outside your door (or
just inside your door if you must). Put them
on as you leave. Choose enclosed shoes,
not open toed, to keep your feet virus-free.
If you are going to work, take
your own food in a disposable
bag. Take a full water bottle
too, in case you get thirsty.
Make sure there is an easily cleanable
reasonable-sized plastic box at your door.
You will need this when you get home.
All your bagged personal items go into
a second plastic box which lives in the
one spot in the car.
Things to buy
Plan your trip to
minimise time away
from the safety of
your home.
While outside
Don't touch anything with your hands that
you don't absolutely need to.
Don't touch your face
Traffic light call
Lift call and floor
Doorknobs
Handrails
buttons

Steering wheels
and gear shifts
Car door
Flat door surfaces
Any item that can be
handles
at chest height
lifted and moved
Assume your hands will get
contaminated and decontaminate
them regularly. Do this while out with
hand washing or if you cannot hand
wash then use some sort of sanitiser.
Hand washing is the most effective.
Push doors with feet preferably or
When your face itches (it will) rub it
with your upper arm. Practise this at
home so you get used to it.
shoulder / elbow if not.
Avoid eating in any communal space. It is
almost impossible not to touch your face
when you eat. No drinks unless you brought
them with you. Unless you are at work,
At store check-outs, do not use cash. Use
contactless payment. If you need to use
your PIN, try to use a knuckle or maybe a
ring finger (index fingers and thumbs are
more likely to be used to touch your face).
try not to eat or drink while out at alI.
Arriving home
Get your items out
of your car box/bag.
Empty the contents of your
paper bags and ziploc
bags into the home box.
Throw the bags away.
No hugs or close greetings
yet. Remove shoes and
leave at the door.
IDENTITY CARD
NAE
A ERE STWEE
CITY, 1245-.
Now clean the items in the home box one at a time – phone, cards etc. Use liberal soap
and water or sanitiser gel if you have lots of this. But soap and water is very effective.
Have a clean spot to place each one after cleaning. Finally clean the plastic box.
-
Now clean the car. Wipe door handle,
steering wheel, gear shift, seat belt
and any surfaces you may have
touched. Clean the car box too.
Go back inside.
Wash your hands again.
You should all be good now
Note: You can clean the ziploc bags thoroughly to reuse them if you want but the
paper bags go in the bin as these cannot be effectively cleaned.
